09375nam a22011655i 9783110733723DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107337237 a10.1515/97831107337232doi  a(DE-B1597)575186  a(OCoLC)1414456434  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPE1074.7b.A29 2024 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a427223/eng/2023122000aAcquisition and Variation in World Englishes :bBridging Paradigms and Rethinking Approaches /ced. by Thorsten Brato, Mirjam Schmalz, Sarah Buschfeld, Manuela Vida-Mannl. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2023] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (VII, 382 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on Language Acquisition [SOLA] ,x1861-4248 ;v6900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 The current role of children and adolescents in World Englishes research -- tPart I: Language in the family -- t2 Language among Trinidadian-heritage children raised in diaspora -- t3 Language use patterns and strategies for children’s English language development: Insights from Chinese descendant mothers in multilingual Malaysia -- t4 Family language policies in Thailand: Multiliteracy practices and Global Englishes -- t5 Parental language ideologies and children’s language use in Singapore – raising speakers of “Standard” English? -- tPart II: Language acquisition and language learning in multilingual contexts -- t6 Syntactic and lexical complexity in CLIL and EFL written production: Evidence for ELF as a WEs paradigm in Turkey -- t7 Investigating child language acquisition from a joint perspective: A comparison of traditional and new L1 speakers of English -- t8 Speech rhythm in Cameroon English: A cross-generational study -- t9 From second to first language: Language shift in Singapore and Ireland -- tPart III: Attitudes and identity -- t10 Children’s language attitudes in a World Englishes community: A focus on St. Kitts -- t11 Youth identity as linguistic identity: Political engagement and language acquisition and use in Hong Kong -- t12 Varieties of English and Third Culture Kids in Hong Kong -- t13 Variation and change in the NURSE vowel in Trinidadian English: An apparent-time analysis of adolescent and adult speakers -- t14 How linguistically tolerant or insecure are school-aged children? A matched-guise, gamified approach for 6- to 12-year-olds in Canada -- t15 Caught between languages and cultures: Exploring linguistic and cultural identity among Maldivian adolescents -- tPart IV: Summary and discussion -- t16 Conclusion and envoi: Language acquisition at the intersection of sociolinguistics and World Englishes research -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is the first of its kind to provide an integrative look at World Englishes, (second) language acquisition, and sociolinguistics in a variety of contexts of English around the globe with a focus on the language of children and adolescents. It thus aims to bridge the paradigm gaps that have been identified between these approaches but have rarely been explored in greater detail. The range of topics includes the areas of first and second language acquisition; sociolinguistic variation and awareness; language use and choice; family language policies; language attitudes and perception; modelling children’s and adolescents’ language in World Englishes; the role of child language acquisition in processes of language change; as well as methodologies of eliciting speech and writing from children and adolescents. The book combines qualitative and quantitative approaches and draws on psycholinguistic, corpus-linguistic, and ethnographic methodologies. What unites the contributions to the volume is that they all address the theoretical implications that a joint approach between World Englishes, sociolinguistics, and language acquisition has, i.e. why it is fruitful and how it can contribute to a deeper understanding of the different research paradigms.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish languagexAcquisition. 0aEnglish languagexVariation. 4aEnglisch. 4aSprache von Kindern und Jugendlichen. 4aSpracherwerb. 4aSprachvarietäten. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aChild Language.  aLanguage Acquisition.  aLanguage Variation And Change.  aWorld Englishes.1 aBrato, Thorsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrato, Thorsten, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuschfeld, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuschfeld, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChan, Vanessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDikilitaş, Kenan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDollinger, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansen Edwards, Jette G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJocuns, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJocuns, Kamolwan Fairee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKöylü, Zeynep, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaag, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeer, Philipp, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMohamed, Naashia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasula, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPfenninger, Simone E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re